'''Nishiteru Shrine'''（にしてるじんじゃ）is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Wakimachi (Mima)|Q28689983|WD=Q28689983|lt=Wakimachi|1=Wakimachi}}, {{ill|lt=Mima|Q857828|WD=Q857828|1=Mima, Tokushima}}, {{ill|lt=Tokushima Prefecture|Q160734|WD=Q160734|1=Tokushima Prefecture}}, and is also called "Tsukigami-no-miya" (Shrine of the Moon Deity). It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinai Shosha|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=shikinai small shrine|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}. Under the former {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, it was {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. The main deity is Tsukuyomi Ōkami ({{ill|WD=Q595520|lt=Tsukuyomi|Q595520|WD=Q595520|WD=Q595520|lt=Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto|1=Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto}}), with the three Munakata goddesses as associated deities: {{ill|lt=Tagitsuhime|Q10932592|WD=Q10932592|lt=Tagitsuhime-no-Mikoto|1=Tagitsuhime}}, {{ill|lt=Takiribime|Q10932870|WD=Q10932870|lt=Tagorihime-no-Mikoto|1=Tagorihime}}, and {{ill|lt=Ichikishimahime|Q11059454|WD=Q11059454|WD=Q11059454|lt=Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto|1=Ichikishima-hime}}.

=== Overview ===
It is located directly below the summit (946{{ill|lt=meter|Q11573|WD=Q11573|lt=m|1=Metre}}) of {{ill|lt=Ōtaki-yama (Sanuki Mountains)|Q11437573|WD=Q11437573|lt=Ōtaki-yama|1=Mount Otaki}}, on the border of {{ill|lt=Mima|Q857828|WD=Q857828|1=Mima, Tokushima}}, Tokushima Prefecture and {{ill|lt=Takamatsu|Q200707|WD=Q200707|1=Takamatsu}}, {{ill|lt=Kagawa Prefecture|Q161454|WD=Q161454|1=Kagawa Prefecture}}. It is treated as a candidate shrine for Tajiki Shrine listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}.

According to shrine tradition, Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto, ruler of the land of night, dispatched Tajikitsuhime-no-Mikoto to Ōtaki-yama as an inspector toward {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}}, and from here had her watch over the {{ill|lt=Seto Inland Sea|Q231312|WD=Q231312|1=Seto Inland Sea}}; this is said to be the shrine's origin.

It is said that in the early {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, {{ill|lt=Kūkai|Q222227|WD=Q222227|1=Kūkai}} practiced ascetic training on this mountain and installed Nishiteru Daigongen, making it a mountain training site of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shinbutsu-shūgō|1=UNKNOWN}}.

Until the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|WD=Q3125096}}, it was called "Nishiteru Gongen." In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it was venerated by the Inada clan, {{ill|lt=chief retainers|Q1316445|WD=Q1316445|1=Karō}} of the {{ill|lt=Tokushima Domain|Q3034557|WD=Q3034557|1=Tokushima Domain}}, who donated 9 chō 8 tan of shrine land, and by the lords of the {{ill|lt=Takamatsu Domain|Q1036915|WD=Q1036915|1=Takamatsu Domain}}, who donated 50 koku for operating expenses as their prayer site.

In the early Meiji era, the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shinbutsu bunri edict|1=UNKNOWN}} separated the shrine from its temple ({{ill|lt=Ōtaki-ji|Q11437672|WD=Q11437672|1=Otaki-ji Temple}}). In Meiji 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was renamed Nishiteru Shrine and ranked as gōsha.

* Legend of the komainu: The shrine has a {{ill|lt=komainu|Q20155846|WD=Q20155846|1=Komainu}} dedicated in {{ill|lt=Tenpō|Q1369045|WD=Q1369045|1=Tenpō}} 14 ({{ill|lt=1843|Q7629|WD=Q7629|1=1843}}). One summer night, a mother and child passing here were chased by a {{ill|lt=wolf|Q18498|WD=Q18498|lt=wolf|1=Wolf}} and fled into the shrine. When the wolf tried to attack them, the komainu drove it away. Due to age, the old statue was moved to a safe place under the honden, and a new pair now stands at the former position by the stone steps.
===Precincts===
* First torii: Beside the road; stone steps continue from here into the precincts.
* Shrine office, kagura hall, and plaza
* Second torii
* Main shrine: haiden and honden
* Inari Shrine: deity is Uga-no-Mitama Ōkami. Haiden and honden are combined in one structure.
* Kumano Shrine: deities are Kumano Gongen, Izanagi Ōkami, and Izanami Ōkami. The Daigongen formerly enshrined at Okunoin of Mt. Ōtaki was moved here in early Shōwa.
* Hachidai Ryūō Shrine: deities are Nanda, Upananda, Sāgara, Vāsuki, Takṣaka, Anavatapta, Manasvin, and Utpalaka. Stone hokora.
* Prayer-stone area and votive horse painting "Tsuki no Mokuba" (painted by Fukuke Haruyo; completion ceremony 2019-11-10)
* Tōmei cedar: height 50 m, said to be 500 years old and known as a "thousand-year cedar." Tradition says the tip shone nightly at the start of the First Sino-Japanese War and went dark at peace talks; a similar event is also said for the Russo-Japanese War.
A parking lot is on the east pass side past Ōtaki-ji on Prefectural Route 106. A pair of komainu was installed at the east entrance in July 2025; walking about 50 m along the approach from there leads into the precincts.
The above shrine buildings line the crest running east from the summit one level above the shrine-office plaza.
